Thread Specification 1.1 (Table 3-2, 7.4.1) requires three different kinds of Mac addresses which will be used on different phases:

- FactoryMAC address: factory assigned IEEE EUI-64;

- HashMac address : first 64 bits of the result of computing SHA-256 over FactoryMAC address (IEEE EUI-64), **used as aExtendedAddress during commissioning process**;

- RandomMac address: random generated 64-bit value, used as aExtendedAddress after commissioning succeed.

We need to follow specification to pass certification tests, since harness will verify that logic. For example, in test case 8.1.1(DUT as Joiner):
- Harness asks user to input DUT's FactoryMAC address;

- Harness calculates DUT's HashMac address by itself;

- This HashMac address will be used as src address filter to verify particular packets.

I think the precision for topK should be more accurate taking into account the order of topK, see details in [http://yongyuan.name/blog/evaluation-of-information-retrieval.html](url).

Please correct me if I've made a mistake.

In the original implementation, precision of topK will decrease as K increases.

```
Top1 | P:0.8892890025575447 | R:0.5064022649687169
Top2 | P:0.6399590792838875 | R:0.7288445630264829
Top3 | P:0.495079283887468 | R:0.8457630870684734
Top4 | P:0.40045524296675195 | R:0.9121509047058687
Top5 | P:0.33090537084398974 | R:0.9421640704190891
