```

So I modified the src/fasttext.cc as follows:
This test function takes the 1/index as weight, So the right results ranking near top1 will have higher precision, and when K increases, precision of topK will not decrease that much. 

```
Top1 | P:0.8892890025575447 | R:0.6546381601916189
Top2 | P:0.914843989769821 | R:0.8268928591726633
Top3 | P:0.9178721227621487 | R:0.8982163358096902
Top4 | P:0.9177379937482252 | R:0.9345346811188172
Top5 | P:0.9168587098607583 | R:0.9513240449803124
Top6 | P:0.9160733901676653 | R:0.9599182397596728
Top7 | P:0.9153916372346097 | R:0.9656490561441976
Top8 | P:0.9145655408830256 | R:0.9699996995899817
Top9 | P:0.9139666362197079 | R:0.9732405472333868
Top10 | P:0.9134275250003393 | R:0.9758264036049207
```



```C++
std::tuple<int64_t, double, double> FastText::test(
    std::istream& in,
    int32_t k,
    real threshold) {
  int32_t nexamples = 0, nlabels = 0, npredictions = 0;
  double precision = 0.0,R_value = 0.0,P_value = 0.0,total_R = 0.0,total_P = 0.0;
  std::vector<int32_t> line, labels;

  while (in.peek() != EOF) {
       precision = 0.0;
        P_value = 0.0;        
       int32_t match_index = 0;
    dict_->getLine(in, line, labels);
    if (labels.size() > 0 && line.size() > 0) {
      std::vector<std::pair<real, int32_t>> modelPredictions;
      model_->predict(line, k, threshold, modelPredictions);
      for (auto it = modelPredictions.cbegin(); it != modelPredictions.cend(); it++) {
               match_index++;
        if (std::find(labels.begin(), labels.end(), it->second)!= labels.end()) {
                precision += 1.0;
                P_value += precision / match_index;
        }
      }
      nexamples++;

      if (precision >0.0){
       total_P += P_value / precision;
       total_R += precision / labels.size();
       }
    }
  }

  return std::tuple<int64_t, double, double>(
      nexamples, total_P/nexamples, total_R/nexamples);
}
```

fastText uses `std::string` to represent text data, which is an alias for `std::basic_string<char>`. It is compiler defined if `char` is signed or `unsigned`. However, the result of 

```
uint32_t Dictionary::hash(const std::string& str) const {
  uint32_t h = 2166136261;
  for (size_t i = 0; i < str.size(); i++) {
    h = h ^ uint32_t(str[i]);
    h = h * 16777619;
  }
  return h;
}
```
depends on if `char` is `signed` or `unsigned`.

To guarantee portability of binary fasttext models, `std::basic_string<signed char>` should be used throughout the library. This should match the current behavior on Linux and OS X (possibly more), but would change the behavior on Android systems for which `char` defaults apparently often to `unsigned char`. Ie. if anyone was using a pretrained binary fasttext model there it was giving wrong results.

